<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888500013&r=1&w=2">List of MX Hosts</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837783700008&r=1&w=2">Craig Partridge &lt;craig () loki ! bbn ! com&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198609">1986-09-26 16:54:26</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026782&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026782&q=raw">body</a>]</b>


    It looks like more and more hosts are converting over to using MX RRs
to route their mail.  Here at CSNET we are interested in getting a better
sense of how many hosts are actually using MX-cognizant mailers.  So we've
set up a mailbox to which system administrators can mail names of the hosts
they maintain that understand MX.  Furthermore we've made the list that is
generated available through the CSNET Info Server for those people interested
in seeing the list.

    To add a host to the list, mail to mxhosts@sh.cs.net.  In the body of
the message simply list the hosts that know about MX, one host per line.
The script attached to the mailbox is very dumb and simply strips the 822
header off the message and appends the rest of the message to our list.
(This is very low-tech but should give us the information we want).

    To retrieve the list, mail the following query to info@sh.cs.net:

--------cut---here---------
request: info
topic: mxlist
request: end
--------cut---here---------

    Please let me know if you encounter problems with this system.

Craig Partridge
CSNET Technical Staff

